<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="ch5-section-expanding-coriolis" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Expanding the Coriolis acceleration</title>

  <p>
    As discussed in <xref ref="appendix-cross-product-term-proof" text="type-global" />
    and shown its <xref ref="aa-earth-setup" text="type-global" /> and <xref ref="aa-earth-setup-atmosphere" text="type-global" />,
    Earth's angular velocity <m>\vec{\Omega}</m> is directed parallel to Earth's axis of rotation,
    pointing upward toward the North Pole.
    Every point on Earth and within Earth's atmosphere is imbued with this same angular velocity.
    Because the unit direction vectors of the local Cartesian coordinate system change orientation with location on Earth,
    at the North Pole, <m>\vec{\Omega}</m> points in the <m>\hat{k}</m> direction,
    while at the South Pole, <m>\vec{\Omega}</m> points in the <m>-\hat{k}</m> direction.
    At the Equator, <m>\vec{\Omega}</m> points in the <m>\hat{j}</m> direction.
    At any other location on Earth's surface or within its atmosphere,
    <m>\vec{\Omega}</m> points partially in the <m>\hat{j}</m> direction
    and partially in the <m>\hat{k}</m> direction,
    as shown in <xref ref="ch5-spherical-coriolis" text="type-global" /> below.
  </p>

  <figure xml:id="ch5-spherical-coriolis">
    <caption>
        Equatorial projection
        showing the unit direction vectors of the local Cartesian coordinate system fixed to a point of interest on Earth's surface
        at radius <m>a \cos{\phi}</m>
        perpendicular to Earth's axis of rotation,
        where <m>a</m> is Earth's mean radius and <m>\phi</m> is latitude.
        Vector <m>\vec{\Omega}</m> shows Earth's constant angular velocity.
        A copy of <m>\vec{\Omega}</m> is moved to the point of interest on Earth's surface.
    </caption>
    <image source="images/ch5-spherical-coriolis.png" width="60%">
      <shortdescription>
        A point on Earth's surface with the local Cartesian coordinate system 
        and Earth's angular velocity vector
        placed at that point.
      </shortdescription>
    </image>
  </figure>

  <p>
    As we learned in <xref ref="aa-section-earth-subsection-all" text="type-global" />,
    <m>\vec{\Omega}</m> expands in spherical coordinates as
  </p>

  <p>
    <md xml:id="eqn-omega-spherical" number="yes">
      \vec{\Omega}
      =
      \Omega \cos{\phi} \, \hat{j}
      + \Omega \sin{\phi} \, \hat{k}
    </md>
  </p>

  <p>
    Consequently, the Coriolis acceleration expands as follows in spherical coordinates:
  </p>

  <p>
    <md>
      <mrow>
        \vec{a}_{COR}
        \amp =
        -2 \, \vec{\Omega} \times \vec{u}
      </mrow>
      <mrow xml:id="eqn-coriolis-spherical" number="yes">
        \amp =
        \left(
            2 \Omega v \sin{\phi} - 2 \Omega w \cos{\phi}
        \right) \hat{i}
        - 2 \Omega u \sin{\phi} \, \hat{j}
        + 2 \Omega u \cos{\phi} \, \hat{k}
      </mrow>
    </md>
  </p>

  <p>
    As we will see in Chapter 8,
    the terms in <xref ref="eqn-coriolis-spherical" text="type-global" />
    with <m>\sin{\phi}</m> tend to be much larger than the terms with <m>\cos{\phi}</m>.
    Taking advantage of the dominance of the <m>\sin{\phi}</m> terms,
    we define the <term>Coriolis parameter</term>
    (also called the <term>Coriolis frequency</term> or <term>Coriolis coefficient</term>)
  </p>

  <p>
    <md xml:id="eqn-coriolis-parameter" number="yes">
      f = 2 \Omega \sin{\phi}
    </md>
  </p>
  
  <p>
    Then <xref ref="eqn-coriolis-spherical" text="type-global" /> can be written
  </p>

  <p>
    <md>
      <mrow>
        \vec{a}_{COR}
        \amp =
        -2 \, \vec{\Omega} \times \vec{u}
      </mrow>
      <mrow xml:id="eqn-coriolis-spherical-parameter" number="yes">
        \amp =
        \left(
            fv - 2 \Omega w \cos{\phi}
        \right) \hat{i}
        - fu \, \hat{j}
        + 2 \Omega u \cos{\phi} \, \hat{k}
      </mrow>
    </md>
  </p>

</section>